# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kalman-filter-stats
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] In estimation theory, the **extended Kalman filter** (**EKF**) is the nonlinear version of the Kalman filter which linearizes about an estimate of the current mean and covariance.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] In the case of well defined transition models, the EKF has been considered the *de facto* standard in the theory of nonlinear state estimation, navigation systems and GPS.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The papers establishing the mathematical foundations of Kalman type filters were published between 1959 and 1961.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Named after the Hungarian-American mathematician, engineer, and inventor Rudolf E.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Kálmán, the Kalman filter is the optimal linear estimator for *linear* system models with additive independent white noise in both the transition and the measurement systems.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Unfortunately, in engineering, most systems are *nonlinear*, so attempts were made to apply this filtering method to nonlinear systems; most of this work was done at NASA Ames.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The EKF adapted techniques from calculus, namely multivariate Taylor series expansions, to linearize a model about a working point.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] If the system model (as described below) is not well known or is inaccurate, then Monte Carlo methods, especially particle filters, are employed for estimation.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Monte Carlo techniques predate the existence of the EKF but are more computationally expensive for any moderately dimensioned state-space.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] In the extended Kalman filter, the state transition and observation models don't need to be linear functions of the state but may instead be differentiable functions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Here **w***k* and **v***k* are the process and observation noises which are both assumed to be zero mean multivariate Gaussian noises with covariance **Q***k* and **R***k* respectively.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The function *f* can be used to compute the predicted state from the previous estimate and similarly the function *h* can be used to compute the predicted measurement from the predicted state.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] However, *f* and *h* cannot be applied to the covariance directly.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Instead a matrix of partial derivatives (the Jacobian) is computed.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] At each time step, the Jacobian is evaluated with current predicted states.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] These matrices can be used in the Kalman filter equations.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] This process essentially linearizes the non-linear function around the current estimate.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] See the Kalman Filter article for notational remarks.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Notation ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{n\mid m}$ represents the estimate of $\mathbf {x}$ at time *n* given observations up to and including at time *m* ≤ *n*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Unlike its linear counterpart, the extended Kalman filter in general is *not* an optimal estimator (it is optimal if the measurement and the state transition model are both linear, as in that case the extended Kalman filter is identical to the regular one).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] In addition, if the initial estimate of the state is wrong, or if the process is modeled incorrectly, the filter may quickly diverge, owing to its linearization.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Another problem with the extended Kalman filter is that the estimated covariance matrix tends to underestimate the true covariance matrix and therefore risks becoming inconsistent in the statistical sense without the addition of "stabilising noise" .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] More generally one should consider the infinite dimensional nature of the nonlinear filtering problem and the inadequacy of a simple mean and variance-covariance estimator to fully represent the optimal filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] In such cases the projection filters have been studied as an alternative, having been applied also to navigation.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Other general nonlinear filtering methods like full particle filters may be considered in this case.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Having stated this, the extended Kalman filter can give reasonable performance, and is arguably the de facto standard in navigation systems and GPS.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Unlike the discrete-time extended Kalman filter, the prediction and update steps are coupled in the continuous-time extended Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Most physical systems are represented as continuous-time models while discrete-time measurements are frequently taken for state estimation via a digital processor.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The update equations are identical to those of discrete-time extended Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The above recursion is a first-order extended Kalman filter (EKF).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Higher order EKFs may be obtained by retaining more terms of the Taylor series expansions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] For example, second and third order EKFs have been described.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] However, higher order EKFs tend to only provide performance benefits when the measurement noise is small.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The typical formulation of the **EKF** involves the assumption of additive process and measurement noise.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] This assumption, however, is not necessary for **EKF** implementation.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The predicted state estimate and measurement residual are evaluated at the mean of the process and measurement noise terms, which is assumed to be zero.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Otherwise, the non-additive noise formulation is implemented in the same manner as the additive noise **EKF**.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Here the original observation covariance matrix ${{\boldsymbol {R}}_{k}}$ is transformed, and the innovation ${\tilde {\boldsymbol {y}}}_{k}$ is defined differently.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The Jacobian matrix ${{\boldsymbol {H}}_{k}}$ is defined as before, but determined from the implicit observation model $h({\boldsymbol {x}}_{k},{\boldsymbol {z}}_{k})$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The iterated extended Kalman filter improves the linearization of the extended Kalman filter by recursively modifying the centre point of the Taylor expansion.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] This reduces the linearization error at the cost of increased computational requirements.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The robust extended Kalman filter arises by linearizing the signal model about the current state estimate and using the linear Kalman filter to predict the next estimate.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] This attempts to produce a locally optimal filter, however, it is not necessarily stable because the solutions of the underlying Riccati equation are not guaranteed to be positive definite.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] One way of improving performance is the faux algebraic Riccati technique which trades off optimality for stability.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The familiar structure of the extended Kalman filter is retained but stability is achieved by selecting a positive definite solution to a faux algebraic Riccati equation for the gain design.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Another way of improving extended Kalman filter performance is to employ the H-infinity results from robust control.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Robust filters are obtained by adding a positive definite term to the design Riccati equation.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The additional term is parametrized by a scalar which the designer may tweak to achieve a trade-off between mean-square-error and peak error performance criteria.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The invariant extended Kalman filter (IEKF) is a modified version of the EKF for nonlinear systems possessing symmetries (or *invariances*).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] It combines the advantages of both the EKF and the recently introduced symmetry-preserving filters.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] Instead of using a linear correction term based on a linear output error, the IEKF uses a geometrically adapted correction term based on an invariant output error; in the same way the gain matrix is not updated from a linear state error, but from an invariant state error.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The main benefit is that the gain and covariance equations converge to constant values on a much bigger set of trajectories than equilibrium points as it is the case for the EKF, which results in a better convergence of the estimation.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] A nonlinear Kalman filter which shows promise as an improvement over the EKF is the unscented Kalman filter (UKF).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] In the UKF, the probability density is approximated by a deterministic sampling of points which represent the underlying distribution as a Gaussian.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The nonlinear transformation of these points are intended to be an estimation of the posterior distribution, the moments of which can then be derived from the transformed samples.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The transformation is known as the unscented transform.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The UKF tends to be more robust and more accurate than the EKF in its estimation of error in all the directions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] A 2012 paper includes simulation results which suggest that some published variants of the UKF fail to be as accurate as the Second Order Extended Kalman Filter (SOEKF), also known as the augmented Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The SOEKF predates the UKF by approximately 35 years with the moment dynamics first described by Bass et al.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The difficulty in implementing any Kalman-type filters for nonlinear state transitions stems from the numerical stability issues required for precision, however the UKF does not escape this difficulty in that it uses linearization as well, namely linear regression.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The stability issues for the UKF generally stem from the numerical approximation to the square root of the covariance matrix, whereas the stability issues for both the EKF and the SOEKF stem from possible issues in the Taylor Series approximation along the trajectory.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] The UKF was in fact predated by the Ensemble Kalman filter, invented by Evensen in 1994.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/extended-kalman-filter] It has the advantage over the UKF that the number of ensemble members used can be much smaller than the state dimension, allowing for applications in very high-dimensional systems, such as weather prediction, with state-space sizes of a billion or more.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The filter is constructed as a mean squared error minimiser, but an alternative derivation of the filter is also provided showing how the filter relates to maximum likelihood statistics.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering has numerous technological applications.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] A common application is for guidance, navigation, and control of vehicles, particularly aircraft, spacecraft and ships positioned dynamically.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Furthermore, Kalman filtering is much applied in time series analysis tasks such as signal processing and econometrics.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering is also important for robotic motion planning and control, and can be used for trajectory optimization.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering also works for modeling the central nervous system's control of movement.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Due to the time delay between issuing motor commands and receiving sensory feedback, the use of Kalman filters provides a realistic model for making estimates of the current state of a motor system and issuing updated commands.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm works via a two-phase process: a *prediction phase* and an *update phase*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In the prediction phase, the Kalman filter produces estimates of the current state variables, including their uncertainties.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Once the outcome of the next measurement (necessarily corrupted with some error, including random noise) is observed, these estimates are updated using a weighted average, with more weight given to estimates with greater certainty.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] It can operate in real time, using only the present input measurements and the state calculated previously and its uncertainty matrix; no additional past information is required.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Optimality of Kalman filtering assumes that errors have a normal (Gaussian) distribution.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Kálmán, "The following assumptions are made about random processes: Physical random phenomena may be thought of as due to primary random sources exciting dynamic systems.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] It is a common misconception (perpetuated in the literature) that the Kalman filter cannot be rigorously applied unless all noise processes are assumed to be Gaussian.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Extensions and generalizations of the method have also been developed, such as the extended Kalman filter and the unscented Kalman filter which work on nonlinear systems.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The basis is a hidden Markov model such that the state space of the latent variables is continuous and all latent and observed variables have Gaussian distributions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering has been used successfully in multi-sensor fusion, and distributed sensor networks to develop distributed or consensus Kalman filtering.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The filtering method is named for Hungarian émigré Rudolf E.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Kálmán, although Thorvald Nicolai Thiele and Peter Swerling developed a similar algorithm earlier.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Bucy of the Johns Hopkins Applied Physics Laboratory contributed to the theory, causing it to be known sometimes as Kalman–Bucy filtering.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman was inspired to derive the Kalman filter by applying state variables to the Wiener filtering problem.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Schmidt is generally credited with developing the first implementation of a Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] He realized that the filter could be divided into two distinct parts, with one part for time periods between sensor outputs and another part for incorporating measurements.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] It was during a visit by Kálmán to the NASA Ames Research Center that Schmidt saw the applicability of Kálmán's ideas to the nonlinear problem of trajectory estimation for the Apollo program resulting in its incorporation in the Apollo navigation computer.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This digital filter is sometimes termed the *Stratonovich–Kalman–Bucy filter* because it is a special case of a more general, nonlinear filter developed by the Soviet mathematician Ruslan Stratonovich.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In fact, some of the special case linear filter's equations appeared in papers by Stratonovich that were published before the summer of 1961, when Kalman met with Stratonovich during a conference in Moscow.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This Kalman filtering was first described and developed partially in technical papers by Swerling (1958), Kalman (1960) and Kalman and Bucy (1961).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filters have been vital in the implementation of the navigation systems of U.S.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Navy nuclear ballistic missile submarines, and in the guidance and navigation systems of cruise missiles such as the U.S.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Air Force's Air Launched Cruise Missile.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] They are also used in the guidance and navigation systems of reusable launch vehicles and the attitude control and navigation systems of spacecraft which dock at the International Space Station.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] As such, it is a common sensor fusion and data fusion algorithm.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Noisy sensor data, approximations in the equations that describe the system evolution, and external factors that are not accounted for, all limit how well it is possible to determine the system's state.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter deals effectively with the uncertainty due to noisy sensor data and, to some extent, with random external factors.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter produces an estimate of the state of the system as an average of the system's predicted state and of the new measurement using a weighted average.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The purpose of the weights is that values with better (i.e., smaller) estimated uncertainty are "trusted" more.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The weights are calculated from the covariance, a measure of the estimated uncertainty of the prediction of the system's state.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The result of the weighted average is a new state estimate that lies between the predicted and measured state, and has a better estimated uncertainty than either alone.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This process is repeated at every time step, with the new estimate and its covariance informing the prediction used in the following iteration.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This means that Kalman filter works recursively and requires only the last "best guess", rather than the entire history, of a system's state to calculate a new state.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The measurements' certainty-grading and current-state estimate are important considerations.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] It is common to discuss the filter's response in terms of the Kalman filter's *gain*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman gain is the weight given to the measurements and current-state estimate, and can be "tuned" to achieve a particular performance.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] With a high gain, the filter places more weight on the most recent measurements, and thus conforms to them more responsively.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] With a low gain, the filter conforms to the model predictions more closely.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] At the extremes, a high gain (close to one) will result in a more jumpy estimated trajectory, while a low gain (close to zero) will smooth out noise but decrease the responsiveness.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] When performing the actual calculations for the filter (as discussed below), the state estimate and covariances are coded into matrices because of the multiple dimensions involved in a single set of calculations.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This allows for a representation of linear relationships between different state variables (such as position, velocity, and acceleration) in any of the transition models or covariances.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] As an example application, consider the problem of determining the precise location of a truck.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The truck can be equipped with a GPS unit that provides an estimate of the position within a few meters.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The GPS estimate is likely to be noisy; readings 'jump around' rapidly, though remaining within a few meters of the real position.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In addition, since the truck is expected to follow the laws of physics, its position can also be estimated by integrating its velocity over time, determined by keeping track of wheel revolutions and the angle of the steering wheel.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This is a technique known as dead reckoning.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Typically, the dead reckoning will provide a very smooth estimate of the truck's position, but it will drift over time as small errors accumulate.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] For this example, the Kalman filter can be thought of as operating in two distinct phases: predict and update.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In the prediction phase, the truck's old position will be modified according to the physical laws of motion (the dynamic or "state transition" model).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Not only will a new position estimate be calculated, but also a new covariance will be calculated as well.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Perhaps the covariance is proportional to the speed of the truck because we are more uncertain about the accuracy of the dead reckoning position estimate at high speeds but very certain about the position estimate at low speeds.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Next, in the update phase, a measurement of the truck's position is taken from the GPS unit.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Along with this measurement comes some amount of uncertainty, and its covariance relative to that of the prediction from the previous phase determines how much the new measurement will affect the updated prediction.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Ideally, as the dead reckoning estimates tend to drift away from the real position, the GPS measurement should pull the position estimate back toward the real position but not disturb it to the point of becoming noisy and rapidly jumping.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is an efficient recursive filter estimating the internal state of a linear dynamic system from a series of noisy measurements.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] It is used in a wide range of engineering and econometric applications from radar and computer vision to estimation of structural macroeconomic models, and is an important topic in control theory and control systems engineering.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Together with the linear-quadratic regulator (LQR), the Kalman filter solves the linear–quadratic–Gaussian control problem (LQG).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter, the linear-quadratic regulator, and the linear–quadratic–Gaussian controller are solutions to what arguably are the most fundamental problems of control theory.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In most applications, the internal state is much larger (has more degrees of freedom) than the few "observable" parameters which are measured.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] However, by combining a series of measurements, the Kalman filter can estimate the entire internal state.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] For the Dempster–Shafer theory, each state equation or observation is considered a special case of a linear belief function and the Kalman filtering is a special case of combining linear belief functions on a join-tree or Markov tree.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Additional methods include belief filtering which use Bayes or evidential updates to the state equations.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] A wide variety of Kalman filters exists by now: Kalman's original formulation - now termed the "simple" Kalman filter, the Kalman–Bucy filter, Schmidt's "extended" filter, the information filter, and a variety of "square-root" filters that were developed by Bierman, Thornton, and many others.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering is based on linear dynamic systems discretized in the time domain.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] They are modeled on a Markov chain built on linear operators perturbed by errors that may include Gaussian noise.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The state of the target system refers to the ground truth (yet hidden) system configuration of interest, which is represented as a vector of real numbers.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] At each discrete time increment, a linear operator is applied to the state to generate the new state, with some noise mixed in, and optionally some information from the controls on the system if they are known.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Then, another linear operator mixed with more noise generates the measurable outputs (i.e., observation) from the true ("hidden") state.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter may be regarded as analogous to the hidden Markov model, with the difference that the hidden state variables have values in a continuous space as opposed to a discrete state space as for the hidden Markov model.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] There is a strong analogy between the equations of a Kalman Filter and those of the hidden Markov model.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] A review of this and other models is given in Roweis and Ghahramani (1999) and Hamilton (1994), Chapter 13.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In order to use the Kalman filter to estimate the internal state of a process given only a sequence of noisy observations, one must model the process in accordance with the following framework.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] As seen below, it is common in many applications that the matrices $\mathbf {F}$ , $\mathbf {H}$ , $\mathbf {Q}$ , $\mathbf {R}$ , and $\mathbf {B}$ are constant across time, in which case their k index may be dropped.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] If $\mathbf {Q}$ is independent of time, one may, following Roweis and Ghahramani, write $\mathbf {w} _{\bullet }$ instead of $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ to emphasize that the noise has no explicit knowledge of time.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Analogously to the situation for $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ , one may write $\mathbf {v} _{\bullet }$ instead of $\mathbf {v} _{k}$ if $\mathbf {R}$ is independent of time.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The initial state, and the noise vectors at each step $\{\mathbf {x} _{0},\mathbf {w} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {w} _{k},\mathbf {v} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {v} _{k}\}$ are all assumed to be mutually independent.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Many real-time dynamic systems do not exactly conform to this model.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In fact, unmodeled dynamics can seriously degrade the filter performance, even when it was supposed to work with unknown stochastic signals as inputs.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The reason for this is that the effect of unmodeled dynamics depends on the input, and, therefore, can bring the estimation algorithm to instability (it diverges).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] On the other hand, independent white noise signals will not make the algorithm diverge.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The problem of distinguishing between measurement noise and unmodeled dynamics is a difficult one and is treated as a problem of control theory using robust control.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is a recursive estimator.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This means that only the estimated state from the previous time step and the current measurement are needed to compute the estimate for the current state.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In contrast to batch estimation techniques, no history of observations and/or estimates is required.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In what follows, the notation ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{n\mid m}$ represents the estimate of $\mathbf {x}$ at time *n* given observations up to and including at time *m* ≤ *n*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm structure of the Kalman filter resembles that of Alpha beta filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter can be written as a single equation; however, it is most often conceptualized as two distinct phases: "Predict" and "Update".
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The predict phase uses the state estimate from the previous timestep to produce an estimate of the state at the current timestep.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This predicted state estimate is also known as the *a priori* state estimate because, although it is an estimate of the state at the current timestep, it does not include observation information from the current timestep.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In the update phase, the innovation (the pre-fit residual), i.e. the difference between the current *a priori* prediction and the current observation information, is multiplied by the optimal Kalman gain and combined with the previous state estimate to refine the state estimate.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This improved estimate based on the current observation is termed the *a posteriori* state estimate.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Typically, the two phases alternate, with the prediction advancing the state until the next scheduled observation, and the update incorporating the observation.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] However, this is not necessary; if an observation is unavailable for some reason, the update may be skipped and multiple prediction procedures performed.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Likewise, if multiple independent observations are available at the same time, multiple update procedures may be performed (typically with different observation matrices **H***k*).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The second formula for the updated (*a posteriori*) estimate covariance above is known as the "Joseph form" that is often used in applications (numerically more stable than the more simple usual formulation).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Proof of the formulae is found in the *derivations* section, where the formula valid for any **K**k is also shown.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This expression reminds us of a linear interpolation, $x=(1-t)(a)+t(b)$ for t between [0,1].
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This expression also resembles the alpha beta filter update step.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] where $\operatorname {E} [\xi ]$ is the expected value of $\xi$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] That is, all estimates have a mean error of zero.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] so covariance matrices accurately reflect the covariance of estimates.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Practical implementation of a Kalman Filter is often difficult due to the difficulty of getting a good estimate of the noise covariance matrices **Q***k* and **R***k*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Extensive research has been done to estimate these covariances from data.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] One practical method of doing this is the *autocovariance least-squares* (ALS) technique that uses the time-lagged autocovariances of routine operating data to estimate the covariances.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The GNU Octave and Matlab code used to calculate the noise covariance matrices using the ALS technique is available online using the GNU General Public License.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Another approach is the *Optimized Kalman Filter* (OKF), which considers the covariance matrices not as representatives of the noise, but rather, as parameters aimed to achieve the most accurate state estimation.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] These two views coincide under the KF assumptions, but often contradict each other in real systems.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Thus, OKF's state estimation is more robust to modeling inaccuracies.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter provides an optimal state estimation in cases where a) the model matches the real system perfectly, b) the entering noise is "white" (uncorrelated), and c) the covariances of the noise are known exactly.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Correlated noise can also be treated using Kalman filters.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Several methods for the noise covariance estimation have been proposed during past decades, including ALS, mentioned in the section above.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] More generally, if the model assumptions do not match the real system perfectly, then optimal state estimation is not necessarily obtained by setting **Q***k* and **R***k* to the covariances of the noise.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Instead, in that case, the parameters **Q***k* and **R***k* may be set to explicitly optimize the state estimation, e.g., using standard supervised learning.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] After the covariances are set, it is useful to evaluate the performance of the filter; i.e., whether it is possible to improve the state estimation quality.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] If the Kalman filter works optimally, the innovation sequence (the output prediction error) is a white noise, therefore the whiteness property of the innovations measures filter performance.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Several different methods can be used for this purpose.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] If the noise terms are distributed in a non-Gaussian manner, methods for assessing performance of the filter estimate, which use probability inequalities or large-sample theory, are known in the literature.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Consider a truck on frictionless, straight rails.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Initially, the truck is stationary at position 0, but it is buffeted this way and that by random uncontrolled forces.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] We measure the position of the truck every Δ*t* seconds, but these measurements are imprecise; we want to maintain a model of the truck's position and velocity.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] We show here how we derive the model from which we create our Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Since $\mathbf {F} ,\mathbf {H} ,\mathbf {R} ,\mathbf {Q}$ are constant, their time indices are dropped.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] where ${\dot {x}}$ is the velocity, that is, the derivative of position with respect to time.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] We assume that between the (*k* − 1) and *k* timestep, uncontrolled forces cause a constant acceleration of *a**k* that is normally distributed with mean 0 and standard deviation *σ**a*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] (there is no $\mathbf {B} u$ term since there are no known control inputs.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The matrix $\mathbf {Q}$ is not full rank (it is of rank one if $\Delta t\neq 0$ ).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Hence, the distribution $N(0,\mathbf {Q} )$ is not absolutely continuous and has no probability density function.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] At each time phase, a noisy measurement of the true position of the truck is made.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Let us suppose the measurement noise *v**k* is also distributed normally, with mean 0 and standard deviation *σ**z*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The filter will then prefer the information from the first measurements over the information already in the model.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] For simplicity, assume that the control input $\mathbf {u} _{k}=\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] A similar equation holds if we include a non-zero control input.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Gain matrices $\mathbf {K} _{k}$ and covariance matrices $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ evolve independently of the measurements $\mathbf {z} _{k}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Since these depend only on the model, and not the measurements, they may be computed offline.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Convergence of the gain matrices $\mathbf {K} _{k}$ to an asymptotic matrix $\mathbf {K} _{\infty }$ applies for conditions established in Walrand and Dimakis.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] If the $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ series converges, then it converges exponentially to an asymptotic $\mathbf {P} _{\infty }$ , assuming non-zero plant noise.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Recent analysis has shown that the *rate and nature* of this convergence can involve multiple coequal modes, including oscillatory components, depending on the eigenstructure of the Jacobian of the above Riccati map evaluated at $\mathbf {P} _{\infty }$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] For the moving truck example described above, with $\Delta t=1$ and $\sigma _{a}^{2}=\sigma _{z}^{2}=\sigma _{x}^{2}=\sigma _{\dot {x}}^{2}=1$ , simulation shows convergence in $10$ iterations.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The asymptotic gain is then computed as before.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter can be derived as a generalized least squares method operating on previous data.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This formula (sometimes known as the **Joseph form** of the covariance update equation) is valid for any value of **K***k*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] It turns out that if **K***k* is the optimal Kalman gain, this can be simplified further as shown below.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is a minimum mean-square error (MMSE) estimator.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] We seek to minimize the expected value of the square of the magnitude of this vector, $\operatorname {E} \left[\left\|\mathbf {x} _{k}-{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k|k}\right\|^{2}\right]$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This is equivalent to minimizing the trace of the *a posteriori* estimate covariance matrix $\mathbf {P} _{k|k}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The trace is minimized when its matrix derivative with respect to the gain matrix is zero.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This gain, which is known as the *optimal Kalman gain*, is the one that yields MMSE estimates when used.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The formula used to calculate the *a posteriori* error covariance can be simplified when the Kalman gain equals the optimal value derived above.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This formula is computationally cheaper and thus nearly always used in practice, but is only correct for the optimal gain.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] If arithmetic precision is unusually low causing problems with numerical stability, or if a non-optimal Kalman gain is deliberately used, this simplification cannot be applied; the *a posteriori* error covariance formula as derived above (Joseph form) must be used.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filtering equations provide an estimate of the state ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k}$ and its error covariance $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ recursively.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The estimate and its quality depend on the system parameters and the noise statistics fed as inputs to the estimator.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This section analyzes the effect of uncertainties in the statistical inputs to the filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] no longer provides the actual error covariance.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] In most real-time applications, the covariance matrices that are used in designing the Kalman filter are different from the actual (true) noise covariances matrices.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This sensitivity analysis describes the behavior of the estimation error covariance when the noise covariances as well as the system matrices $\mathbf {F} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {H} _{k}$ that are fed as inputs to the filter are incorrect.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Thus, the sensitivity analysis describes the robustness (or sensitivity) of the estimator to misspecified statistical and parametric inputs to the estimator.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This discussion is limited to the error sensitivity analysis for the case of statistical uncertainties.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Here the actual noise covariances are denoted by $\mathbf {Q} _{k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}^{a}$ respectively, whereas the design values used in the estimator are $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ respectively.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The actual error covariance is denoted by $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ as computed by the Kalman filter is referred to as the Riccati variable.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The recursive expressions for $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ are identical except for the presence of $\mathbf {Q} _{k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}^{a}$ in place of the design values $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ respectively.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Researches have been done to analyze Kalman filter system's robustness.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] One problem with the Kalman filter is its numerical stability.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] If the process noise covariance **Q***k* is small, round-off error often causes a small positive eigenvalue of the state covariance matrix **P** to be computed as a negative number.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This renders the numerical representation of **P** indefinite, while its true form is positive-definite.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Positive definite matrices have the property that they have a factorization into the product of a non-singular, lower-triangular matrix **S** and its transpose : **P** = **S**·**S**T .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The factor **S** can be computed efficiently using the Cholesky factorization algorithm.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This product form of the covariance matrix **P** is guaranteed to be symmetric, and for all 1 <= k <= n, the k-th diagonal element **P**kk is equal to the square of the euclidean norm of the k-th row of **S**, which is necessarily positive.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Between the two, the U-D factorization uses the same amount of storage, and somewhat less computation, and is the most commonly used triangular factorization.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Efficient algorithms for the Kalman prediction and update steps in the factored form were developed by G.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The **L**·**D**·**L**T decomposition of the innovation covariance matrix **S**k is the basis for another type of numerically efficient and robust square root filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm starts with the LU decomposition as implemented in the Linear Algebra PACKage (LAPACK).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] These results are further factored into the **L**·**D**·**L**T structure with methods given by Golub and Van Loan (algorithm 4.1.2) for a symmetric nonsingular matrix.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] Any singular covariance matrix is pivoted so that the first diagonal partition is nonsingular and well-conditioned.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The pivoting algorithm must retain any portion of the innovation covariance matrix directly corresponding to observed state-variables **H**k·**x**k|k-1 that are associated with auxiliary observations in **y**k.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The **l**·**d**·**l**t square-root filter requires orthogonalization of the observation vector.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This may be done with the inverse square-root of the covariance matrix for the auxiliary variables using Method 2 in Higham (2002, p.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is efficient for sequential data processing on central processing units (CPUs), but in its original form it is inefficient on parallel architectures such as graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] It is however possible to express the filter-update routine in terms of an associative operator using the formulation in Särkkä and García-Fernández (2021).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] The filter solution can then be retrieved by the use of a prefix sum algorithm which can be efficiently implemented on GPU.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p01] This reduces the computational complexity from $O(N)$ in the number of time steps to $O(\log(N))$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The Kalman filter can be presented as one of the simplest dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The Kalman filter calculates estimates of the true values of states recursively over time using incoming measurements and a mathematical process model.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Similarly, recursive Bayesian estimation calculates estimates of an unknown probability density function (PDF) recursively over time using incoming measurements and a mathematical process model.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] In recursive Bayesian estimation, the true state is assumed to be an unobserved Markov process, and the measurements are the observed states of a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Because of the Markov assumption, the true state is conditionally independent of all earlier states given the immediately previous state.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Similarly, the measurement at the *k*-th timestep is dependent only upon the current state and is conditionally independent of all other states given the current state.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] However, when a Kalman filter is used to estimate the state **x**, the probability distribution of interest is that associated with the current states conditioned on the measurements up to the current timestep.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This is achieved by marginalizing out the previous states and dividing by the probability of the measurement set.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This results in the *predict* and *update* phases of the Kalman filter written probabilistically.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The probability distribution of the update is proportional to the product of the measurement likelihood and the predicted state.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The PDF at the previous timestep is assumed inductively to be the estimated state and covariance.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This is justified because, as an optimal estimator, the Kalman filter makes best use of the measurements, therefore the PDF for $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ given the measurements $\mathbf {Z} _{k}$ is the Kalman filter estimate.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Related to the recursive Bayesian interpretation described above, the Kalman filter can be viewed as a generative model, i.e., a process for *generating* a stream of random observations **z** = (**z**0, **z**1, **z**2, ...).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This process has identical structure to the hidden Markov model, except that the discrete state and observations are replaced with continuous variables sampled from Gaussian distributions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] In some applications, it is useful to compute the *probability* that a Kalman filter with a given set of parameters (prior distribution, transition and observation models, and control inputs) would generate a particular observed signal.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This probability is known as the marginal likelihood because it integrates over ("marginalizes out") the values of the hidden state variables, so it can be computed using only the observed signal.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The marginal likelihood can be useful to evaluate different parameter choices, or to compare the Kalman filter against other models using Bayesian model comparison.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] It is straightforward to compute the marginal likelihood as a side effect of the recursive filtering computation.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] i.e., a product of Gaussian densities, each corresponding to the density of one observation **z***k* under the current filtering distribution $\mathbf {H} _{k}{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k-1},\mathbf {S} _{k}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This can easily be computed as a simple recursive update; however, to avoid numeric underflow, in a practical implementation it is usually desirable to compute the *log* marginal likelihood $\ell =\log p(\mathbf {z} )$ instead.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] where $d_{y}$ is the dimension of the measurement vector.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] An important application where such a (log) likelihood of the observations (given the filter parameters) is used is multi-target tracking.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] For example, consider an object tracking scenario where a stream of observations is the input, however, it is unknown how many objects are in the scene (or, the number of objects is known but is greater than one).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] For such a scenario, it can be unknown apriori which observations/measurements were generated by which object.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] A multiple hypothesis tracker (MHT) typically will form different track association hypotheses, where each hypothesis can be considered as a Kalman filter (for the linear Gaussian case) with a specific set of parameters associated with the hypothesized object.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Thus, it is important to compute the likelihood of the observations for the different hypotheses under consideration, such that the most-likely one can be found.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Additionally, the information filter allows for system information initialization according to ${I_{1|0}=P_{1|0}^{-1}=0}$ , which would not be possible for the regular Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] In the information filter, or inverse covariance filter, the estimated covariance and estimated state are replaced by the information matrix and information vector respectively.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The information update now becomes a trivial sum.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The main advantage of the information filter is that *N* measurements can be filtered at each time step simply by summing their information matrices and vectors.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] To predict the information filter the information matrix and vector can be converted back to their state space equivalents, or alternatively the information space prediction can be used.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The optimal fixed-lag smoother provides the optimal estimate of ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k-N\mid k}$ for a given fixed-lag N using the measurements from $\mathbf {z} _{1}$ to $\mathbf {z} _{k}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The optimal fixed-interval smoother provides the optimal estimate of ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid n}$ ( $k<n$ ) using the measurements from a fixed interval $\mathbf {z} _{1}$ to $\mathbf {z} _{n}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] There are several smoothing algorithms in common use.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The Rauch–Tung–Striebel (RTS) smoother is an efficient two-pass algorithm for fixed interval smoothing.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The forward pass is the same as the regular Kalman filter algorithm.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] These *filtered* a-priori and a-posteriori state estimates ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k-1}$ , ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k}$ and covariances $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k-1}$ , $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ are saved for use in the backward pass (for retrodiction).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] In the backward pass, we compute the *smoothed* state estimates ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid n}$ and covariances $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid n}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] $\mathbf {x} _{k\mid k}$ is the a-posteriori state estimate of timestep k and $\mathbf {x} _{k+1\mid k}$ is the a-priori state estimate of timestep $k+1$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The same notation applies to the covariance.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] An alternative to the RTS algorithm is the modified Bryson–Frazier (MBF) fixed interval smoother developed by Bierman.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This also uses a backward pass that processes data saved from the Kalman filter forward pass.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The equations for the backward pass involve the recursive computation of data which are used at each observation time to compute the smoothed state and covariance.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] An important advantage of the MBF is that it does not require finding the inverse of the covariance matrix.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Bierman's derivation is based on the RTS smoother, which assumes that the underlying distributions are Gaussian.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] However, a derivation of the MBF based on the concept of the fixed point smoother, which does not require the Gaussian assumption, is given by Gibbs.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The MBF can also be used to perform consistency checks on the filter residuals and the difference between the value of a filter state after an update and the smoothed value of the state, that is $\mathbf {x} _{k\mid k}-\mathbf {x} _{k\mid n}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The minimum-variance smoother can attain the best-possible error performance, provided that the models are linear, their parameters and the noise statistics are known precisely.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This smoother is a time-varying state-space generalization of the optimal non-causal Wiener filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The smoother calculations are done in two passes.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The above system is known as the inverse Wiener-Hopf factor.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The backward recursion is the adjoint of the above forward system.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The result of the backward pass $\beta _{k}$ may be calculated by operating the forward equations on the time-reversed $\alpha _{k}$ and time reversing the result.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] which is identical to the minimum-variance Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The above solutions minimize the variance of the output estimation error.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Note that the Rauch–Tung–Striebel smoother derivation assumes that the underlying distributions are Gaussian, whereas the minimum-variance solutions do not.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Optimal smoothers for state estimation and input estimation can be constructed similarly.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] A continuous-time version of the above smoother is described in.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Expectation–maximization algorithms may be employed to calculate approximate maximum likelihood estimates of unknown state-space parameters within minimum-variance filters and smoothers.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Often uncertainties remain within problem assumptions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] A smoother that accommodates uncertainties can be designed by adding a positive definite term to the Riccati equation.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] In cases where the models are nonlinear, step-wise linearizations may be within the minimum-variance filter and smoother recursions (extended Kalman filtering).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Pioneering research on the perception of sounds at different frequencies was conducted by Fletcher and Munson in the 1930s.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Their work led to a standard way of weighting measured sound levels within investigations of industrial noise and hearing loss.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Frequency weightings have since been used within filter and controller designs to manage performance within bands of interest.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Typically, a frequency shaping function is used to weight the average power of the error spectral density in a specified frequency band.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Let $\mathbf {y} -{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}$ denote the output estimation error exhibited by a conventional Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Also, let $\mathbf {W}$ denote a causal frequency weighting transfer function.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The optimum solution which minimizes the variance of $\mathbf {W} \left(\mathbf {y} -{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}\right)$ arises by simply constructing $\mathbf {W} ^{-1}{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The design of $\mathbf {W}$ remains an open question.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] One way of proceeding is to identify a system which generates the estimation error and setting $\mathbf {W}$ equal to the inverse of that system.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This procedure may be iterated to obtain mean-square error improvement at the cost of increased filter order.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The same technique can be applied to smoothers.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The basic Kalman filter is limited to a linear assumption.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] More complex systems, however, can be nonlinear.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The nonlinearity can be associated either with the process model or with the observation model or with both.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The most common variants of Kalman filters for non-linear systems are the Extended Kalman Filter and Unscented Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The suitability of which filter to use depends on the non-linearity indices of the process and observation model.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] In the extended Kalman filter (EKF), the state transition and observation models need not be linear functions of the state but may instead be nonlinear functions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] These functions are of differentiable type.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] At each timestep the Jacobian is evaluated with current predicted states.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This process essentially linearizes the nonlinear function around the current estimate.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] When the state transition and observation models—that is, the predict and update functions f and h —are highly nonlinear, the extended Kalman filter can give particularly poor performance.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This is because the covariance is propagated through linearization of the underlying nonlinear model.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The unscented Kalman filter (UKF) uses a deterministic sampling technique known as the unscented transformation (UT) to pick a minimal set of sample points (called sigma points) around the mean.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The sigma points are then propagated through the nonlinear functions, from which a new mean and covariance estimate are formed.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The resulting filter depends on how the transformed statistics of the UT are calculated and which set of sigma points are used.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] It should be remarked that it is always possible to construct new UKFs in a consistent way.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] For certain systems, the resulting UKF more accurately estimates the true mean and covariance.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This can be verified with Monte Carlo sampling or Taylor series expansion of the posterior statistics.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Typically, $\mathbf {A}$ is obtained via Cholesky decomposition of $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] With some care the filter equations can be expressed in such a way that $\mathbf {A}$ is evaluated directly without intermediate calculations of $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This is referred to as the *square-root unscented Kalman filter*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The weight of the mean value, $W_{0}$ , can be chosen arbitrarily.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] $\alpha$ and $\kappa$ control the spread of the sigma points. $\beta$ is related to the distribution of x .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Note that this is an overparameterization in the sense that any one of $\alpha$ , $\beta$ and $\kappa$ can be chosen arbitrarily.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Appropriate values depend on the problem at hand, but a typical recommendation is $\alpha =1$ , $\beta =0$ , and $\kappa \approx 3L/2$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] If the true distribution of x is Gaussian, $\beta =2$ is optimal.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] As with the EKF, the UKF prediction can be used independently from the UKF update, in combination with a linear (or indeed EKF) update, or vice versa.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Given estimates of the mean and covariance, ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k-1\mid k-1}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ , one obtains $N=2L+1$ sigma points as described in the section above.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The sigma points are propagated through the transition function *f*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The propagated sigma points are weighed to produce the predicted mean and covariance.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] where $W_{j}^{a}$ are the first-order weights of the original sigma points, and $W_{j}^{c}$ are the second-order weights.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The matrix $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ is the covariance of the transition noise, $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] These sigma points are transformed through the measurement function h .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Then the empirical mean and covariance of the transformed points are calculated.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] where $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ is the covariance matrix of the observation noise, $\mathbf {v} _{k}$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] This replaces the generative specification of the standard Kalman filter with a discriminative model for the latent states given observations.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Such an approach proves particularly useful when the dimensionality of the observations is much greater than that of the latent states and can be used to build filters that are particularly robust to nonstationarities in the observation model.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Adaptive Kalman filters allow to adapt for process dynamics which are not modeled in the process model $\mathbf {F} (t)$ , which happens for example in the context of a maneuvering target when a constant velocity (reduced order) Kalman filter is employed for tracking.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Kalman–Bucy filtering (named for Richard Snowden Bucy) is a continuous time version of Kalman filtering.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] where $\mathbf {Q} (t)$ and $\mathbf {R} (t)$ represent the intensities of the two white noise terms $\mathbf {w} (t)$ and $\mathbf {v} (t)$ , respectively.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The distinction between the prediction and update steps of discrete-time Kalman filtering does not exist in continuous time.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The second differential equation, for the covariance, is an example of a Riccati equation.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Nonlinear generalizations to Kalman–Bucy filters include continuous time extended Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Most physical systems are represented as continuous-time models while discrete-time measurements are made frequently for state estimation via a digital processor.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The prediction equations are derived from those of continuous-time Kalman filter without update from measurements, i.e., $\mathbf {K} (t)=0$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The predicted state and covariance are calculated respectively by solving a set of differential equations with the initial value equal to the estimate at the previous step.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] For the case of linear time invariant systems, the continuous time dynamics can be exactly discretized into a discrete time system using matrix exponentials.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The update equations are identical to those of the discrete-time Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] The traditional Kalman filter has also been employed for the recovery of sparse, possibly dynamic, signals from noisy observations.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Recent works utilize notions from the theory of compressed sensing/sampling, such as the restricted isometry property and related probabilistic recovery arguments, for sequentially estimating the sparse state in intrinsically low-dimensional systems.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/kalman-filter-p02] Since linear Gaussian state-space models lead to Gaussian processes, Kalman filters can be viewed as sequential solvers for Gaussian process regression.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Particle filtering uses a set of particles (also called samples) to represent the posterior distribution of a stochastic process given the noisy and/or partial observations.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The state-space model can be nonlinear and the initial state and noise distributions can take any form required.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Particle filter techniques provide a well-established methodology for generating samples from the required distribution without requiring assumptions about the state-space model or the state distributions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] However, these methods do not perform well when applied to very high-dimensional systems.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Particle filters update their prediction in an approximate (statistical) manner.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The samples from the distribution are represented by a set of particles; each particle has a likelihood weight assigned to it that represents the probability of that particle being sampled from the probability density function.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Weight disparity leading to weight collapse is a common issue encountered in these filtering algorithms.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] However, it can be mitigated by including a resampling step before the weights become uneven.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Several adaptive resampling criteria can be used including the variance of the weights and the relative entropy concerning the uniform distribution.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In the resampling step, the particles with negligible weights are replaced by new particles in the proximity of the particles with higher weights.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] From the statistical and probabilistic point of view, particle filters may be interpreted as mean-field particle interpretations of Feynman-Kac probability measures.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] These particle integration techniques were developed in molecular chemistry and computational physics by Theodore E.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Harris and Herman Kahn in 1951, Marshall N.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Rosenbluth in 1955, and more recently by Jack H.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In computational physics, these Feynman-Kac type path particle integration methods are also used in Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically Diffusion Monte Carlo methods.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Feynman-Kac interacting particle methods are also strongly related to mutation-selection genetic algorithms currently used in evolutionary computation to solve complex optimization problems.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The particle filter methodology is used to solve Hidden Markov Model (HMM) and nonlinear filtering problems.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] From a statistical and probabilistic viewpoint, particle filters belong to the class of branching/genetic type algorithms, and mean-field type interacting particle methodologies.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The interpretation of these particle methods depends on the scientific discipline.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In Evolutionary Computing, mean-field genetic type particle methodologies are often used as heuristic and natural search algorithms (a.k.a.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In computational physics and molecular chemistry, they are used to solve Feynman-Kac path integration problems or to compute Boltzmann-Gibbs measures, top eigenvalues, and ground states of Schrödinger operators.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In Biology and Genetics, they represent the evolution of a population of individuals or genes in some environment.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The origins of mean-field type evolutionary computational techniques can be traced back to 1950 and 1954 with Alan Turing's work on genetic type mutation-selection learning machines and the articles by Nils Aall Barricelli at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The first trace of particle filters in statistical methodology dates back to the mid-1950s; the 'Poor Man's Monte Carlo', that was proposed by John Hammersley et al., in 1954, contained hints of the genetic type particle filtering methods used today.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In 1963, Nils Aall Barricelli simulated a genetic type algorithm to mimic the ability of individuals to play a simple game.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In evolutionary computing literature, genetic-type mutation-selection algorithms became popular through the seminal work of John Holland in the early 1970s, particularly his book published in 1975.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In Biology and Genetics, the Australian geneticist Alex Fraser also published in 1957 a series of papers on the genetic type simulation of artificial selection of organisms.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The computer simulation of the evolution by biologists became more common in the early 1960s, and the methods were described in books by Fraser and Burnell (1970) and Crosby (1973).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Fraser's simulations included all of the essential elements of modern mutation-selection genetic particle algorithms.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] From the mathematical viewpoint, the conditional distribution of the random states of a signal given some partial and noisy observations is described by a Feynman-Kac probability on the random trajectories of the signal weighted by a sequence of likelihood potential functions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically Diffusion Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mean-field genetic type particle approximation of Feynman-Kac path integrals.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The origins of Quantum Monte Carlo methods are often attributed to Enrico Fermi and Robert Richtmyer who developed in 1948 a mean-field particle interpretation of neutron chain reactions, but the first heuristic-like and genetic type particle algorithm (a.k.a.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Resampled or Reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods) for estimating ground state energies of quantum systems (in reduced matrix models) is due to Jack H.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] One can also quote the earlier seminal works of Theodore E.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Harris and Herman Kahn in particle physics, published in 1951, using mean-field but heuristic-like genetic methods for estimating particle transmission energies.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In molecular chemistry, the use of genetic heuristic-like particle methodologies (a.k.a. pruning and enrichment strategies) can be traced back to 1955 with the seminal work of Marshall N.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The use of genetic particle algorithms in advanced signal processing and Bayesian inference is more recent.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In January 1993, Genshiro Kitagawa developed a "Monte Carlo filter", a slightly modified version of this article appeared in 1996.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Gordon et al., published in their seminal work an application of genetic type algorithm in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The authors named their algorithm 'the bootstrap filter', and demonstrated that compared to other filtering methods, their bootstrap algorithm does not require any assumption about that state space or the noise of the system.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Independently, the ones by Pierre Del Moral and Himilcon Carvalho, Pierre Del Moral, André Monin, and Gérard Salut on particle filters published in the mid-1990s.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Particle filters were also developed in signal processing in early 1989–1992 by P.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Salut in the LAAS-CNRS in a series of restricted and classified research reports with STCAN (Service Technique des Constructions et Armes Navales), the IT company DIGILOG, and the LAAS-CNRS (the Laboratory for Analysis and Architecture of Systems) on RADAR/SONAR and GPS signal processing problems.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The mathematical foundations and the first rigorous analysis of these particle algorithms are due to Pierre Del Moral in 1996.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The article also contains proof of the unbiased properties of a particle approximation of likelihood functions and unnormalized conditional probability measures.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The unbiased particle estimator of the likelihood functions presented in this article is used today in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Dan Crisan, Jessica Gaines, and Terry Lyons, as well as Pierre Del Moral, and Terry Lyons, created branching-type particle techniques with various population sizes around the end of the 1990s.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Miclo made more advances in this subject in 2000.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Pierre Del Moral and Alice Guionnet proved the first central limit theorems in 1999, and Pierre Del Moral and Laurent Miclo proved them in 2000.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The first uniform convergence results concerning the time parameter for particle filters were developed at the end of the 1990s by Pierre Del Moral and Alice Guionnet.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The first rigorous analysis of genealogical tree-based particle filter smoothers is due to P.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The theory on Feynman-Kac particle methodologies and related particle filter algorithms was developed in 2000 and 2004 in the books.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] These abstract probabilistic models encapsulate genetic type algorithms, particle, and bootstrap filters, interacting Kalman filters (a.k.a.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Rao–Blackwellized particle filter), importance sampling and resampling style particle filter techniques, including genealogical tree-based and particle backward methodologies for solving filtering and smoothing problems.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] A particle filter's goal is to estimate the posterior density of state variables given observation variables.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The particle filter is intended for use with a hidden Markov Model, in which the system includes both hidden and observable variables.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The observable variables (observation process) are linked to the hidden variables (state-process) via a known functional form.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Similarly, the probabilistic description of the dynamical system defining the evolution of the state variables is known.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] A generic particle filter estimates the posterior distribution of the hidden states using the observation measurement process.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] the filtering problem is to estimate **sequentially** the values of the hidden states $X_{k}$ , given the values of the observation process $Y_{0},\cdots ,Y_{k},$ at any time step *k*.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The particle filter methodology provides an approximation of these conditional probabilities using the empirical measure associated with a genetic type particle algorithm.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In contrast, the Markov Chain Monte Carlo or importance sampling approach would model the full posterior $p(x_{0},x_{1},...,x_{k}|y_{0},y_{1},...,y_{k})$ .
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] where both $W_{k}$ and $V_{k}$ are mutually independent sequences with known probability density functions and *g* and *h* are known functions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] These two equations can be viewed as state space equations and look similar to the state space equations for the Kalman filter.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] If the functions *g* and *h* in the above example are linear, and if both $W_{k}$ and $V_{k}$ are Gaussian, the Kalman filter finds the exact Bayesian filtering distribution.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] If not, Kalman filter-based methods are a first-order approximation (EKF) or a second-order approximation (UKF in general, but if the probability distribution is Gaussian a third-order approximation is possible).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The assumption that the initial distribution and the transitions of the Markov chain are continuous for the Lebesgue measure can be relaxed.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The continuous assumption on the Markov transitions of $X_{k}$ is only used to derive in an informal (and rather abusive) way different formulae between posterior distributions using the Bayes' rule for conditional densities.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In certain problems, the conditional distribution of observations, given the random states of the signal, may fail to have a density; the latter may be impossible or too complex to compute.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In this situation, an additional level of approximation is necessitated.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] for some sequence of independent random variables ${\mathcal {V}}_{k}$ with known probability density functions.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] These probabilistic techniques are closely related to Approximate Bayesian Computation (ABC).
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] In the context of particle filters, these ABC particle filtering techniques were introduced in 1998 by P.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Particle filters are also an approximation, but with enough particles they can be much more accurate.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] The nonlinear filtering problem consists in computing these conditional distributions sequentially.
[src:kalman-filter-stats/particle-filter-p01] Feynman-Kac path integration models arise in a variety of scientific disciplines, including in computational physics, biology, information theory and computer sciences.
